["Fluent Validation is a popular .NET library for building strongly-typed validation rules. It is often used with ASP.NET Core applications, which can also take advantage of Swagger (now known as OpenAPI) for API documentation. To integrate Fluent Validation with automatic Swagger documentation generation, you'll typically be using the Swashbuckle.AspNetCore library, which generates Swagger documentation for ASP.NET Core Web API projects.

Here's how you can set up Fluent Validation with Swagger documentation:

1. Install the necessary NuGet packages:
You need to install the following packages if you haven't already:

- FluentValidation.AspNetCore
- Swashbuckle.AspNetCore

You can install them using the NuGet package manager or the dotnet CLI:

```shell
dotnet add package FluentValidation.AspNetCore
dotnet add package Swashbuckle.AspNetCore
```

2. Configure Fluent Validation in `Startup.cs` or `Program.cs`:
Within the `ConfigureServices` method, register Fluent Validation alongside your MVC or API services.

In `Startup.cs`:

```csharp
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    services.AddControllers()
        .AddFluentValidation(fv => fv.RegisterValidatorsFromAssemblyContaining<Startup>());
    // Other service configurations

    services.AddSwaggerGen();
}
```

In `Program.cs` (for .NET 6+):

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddControllers()
    .AddFluentValidation(fv => fv.RegisterValidatorsFromAssemblyContaining<Program>());

builder.Services.AddSwaggerGen();
// Other service configurations

var app = builder.Build();
```

3. Configure Swagger to use the Fluent Validation rules:
This step is often not required because Swashbuckle will automatically generate schema information for your API endpoints and include the validation rules you've set up with Fluent Validation. However, if you want to customize the behavior or include additional information in the Swagger documentation, you can configure Swashbuckle accordingly.

In `Startup.cs`:

```csharp
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    // Other service configurations

    services.AddSwaggerGen(options =>
    {
        // Customizations go here
    });
}
```

4. Enable Swagger middleware in `Startup.cs` or `Program.cs`:
You need to add the Swagger middleware to the HTTP request pipeline to serve the generated Swagger JSON and the Swagger UI.

In `Startup.cs`:

```csharp
public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
{
    // Other middleware configurations

    app.UseSwagger();
    app.UseSwaggerUI();
}
```

In `Program.cs`:

```csharp
// Other configurations

app.UseSwagger();
app.UseSwaggerUI();

app.Run();
```

5. Define your validators:
Create validation classes by inheriting from `AbstractValidator<T>` where `T` is the type you want to validate.

Example:

```csharp
using FluentValidation;

public class MyModelValidator : AbstractValidator<MyModel>
{
    public MyModelValidator()
    {
        RuleFor(x => x.Property).NotEmpty();
        // Other rules
    }
}
```

6. Apply validators to your models:
You can now apply your validators to the models you use in your API endpoints.

```csharp
public class MyModel
{
    public string Property { get; set; }
}
```

Swashbuckle will automatically reflect the validation rules from Fluent Validation in the Swagger documentation. When you navigate to the Swagger UI, you should see the validation rules applied as part of the model schemas.

Remember, the actual steps may vary slightly based on the version of ASP.NET Core you are using or specific configurations of your project. However, the general process will be similar to the one outlined above."]

